title: Mashup Sliced Wade's Geared Extruder for Makerbot

description.text:
This is a mashup/redesign of several designs and documents, for me the most useful to undertand Wade's extruder was certainly droftarts' pdf http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8072 and KurtcCircuit's Sliced Wade's Geared Nema 17 Extruder http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:5548
Wade's original design: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1794 Some ideas like the smooth central PTFE contact surfaces are derived from the Makerbot^s plastruder MK5 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:3290 The steppers inclination allows for better equilibrating the center of gravity in relation to the stand and platform, while providing a reasonably straight path for the filament. Cut in 6.75 mm plywood and 5.3 mm PTFE (the three central layers), this thing feels sturdy and heavy like a tank. As a consequence, it is mainly adapted to configurations with a stationary extruder like the Makerbot, and Bowden extruders. Both gears were dipped in marine (very fluid) epoxy, assembled, and allowed to cure for several days, the resulting composite has very interesting resistance and surface properties. This is a work in progress: I see a need to implement some real quick release lever system instead of the quick hack (works but has some kludges, would not allow a quick change of filaments for example). For now the first aim was to get printing quickly with the homegrown/pirated cupcake, and printing it is. Video: http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VPwZG3rEj5U
Attached to it is a standard reprap hotend (needed some additional PTFE rod to get to the appropriate length). Driven by a RAMPS board.

By now most of the initial goofs and brain farts (related to asymetric design) have been ironed out of the dxf files. Adapt the cut depths to the material you have locally. For savings, you can use plywood instead of PTFE for the three central layers, but IMHO it adds to the good working. Please note that both gears perimeters have cutter correction already designed in (for a 1.5mm diamenter cutter) if lasercutting this must be modified. The M8 bolt needs hobbing, the exact location is further away than in "standard" wades bolts sold around. I chose to dremel it. This might be of some use: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:10110 or this: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:9291

title: Customizable Adjustment Wheel Mark 2 For Cutting

description.text: This is the same as my regular mark 2, but modified for exporting .dxf files.  I added the option of 1mm circles in the center of every hole for those of you (like me) who are printing it out, gluing it to a piece of wood, and cutting it out.

If you're using a laser cutter you probably want to turn off the center holes.  You might also want to make a few of these and stack them, depending on the size of your nut.  If, like me, you are cutting this out of wood, then print it out, glue it to your board, and slap it in a drill press (or use a hand drill if you have to).  First, drill out the notches, then cut out the wheel itself.  If you have a hole saw you can make this a lot easier on yourself.  Otherwise a jigsaw will work.  Finally, drill out the center hole and finish it up with files or a jigsaw.  Press fit it onto your nut and possibly glue it.

title: Robo3D Lead Screw Upgrade - Quick Printing Hole Cover

description.text:
I added the Lead Screw upgrade to my Robo3D R1 and then found I had this hole exposing the screw connected to the motor. I was afraid little pieces of plastic can fly in there and damage something.   
I wanted a solution but I didn't want to take everything apart to implement in.   
So I came up with this quick printing hole cover (3 min max) that is easy to slide on the screw without messing with the thread.

Print Info
  • Make sure you print with the hole facing down
  • PLA
  • .3mm Layer Height
  • No Support
  • 20% Infill (keeps it flexible but strong)
    (recommend you scale up 1% to make sure printing excess doesn't mess with threads on lead screw)
    • I purposely made a small thin first layer and then bridged the second layer to cause that mesh look but also for flexibility. I found when I had a full first layer it would be too stiff to print with PLA.

title: Laptop internal camera cover for the paranoid

description.text:
Call me paranoid, but I don't like the idea of having a camera pointed at me every second I am on my computer.  I have a Lenovo laptop that has an internal camera.  Sure, it has an indicator LED next to it that illuminates when the camera is on, but I happen to know that these indicator LED's can be turned off via software.  If some hacker ever gets into my computer, he/she can see me and everything around me.  I'm way too paranoid for that. So, I drew up a litte sliding cover to fix the problem.  Afix it with either double sided tape or your favorite glue, e.g. super glue or hot glue. 
While this was made to fit the camera on the Lenovo laptops, I've sure it will fit 99% of all laptop cameras.
Just use double-sided tape or use some glue like super glue or hot glue to stick this over your laptop camera lens.  Open the slide door when you want the camera to see you.

title: Toy License Plate Generator - Washington State

description.text: I wrote this OpenSCAD code to create toy license/name plates for my son and his friends to put on their bikes. It is a fairly accurate reproduction of the current WA plate layout, with a 3D rendering of Mt. Rainier as background. You need the freeware parametric CAD program OpenSCAD, which you can get here: http://www.openscad.org/ I've included an example STL, but unless your name is Elvis, you will probably want to generate your own. You need my .scad code, and (if you want to use my Mt. Rainier background) you need the mount_rainier_4mm.stl model. Just download the files and follow the instructions. I've also included some rough directions for generating your own background if you want another state or picture, but that will require a bit of tinkering. Have fun. I'd love to see remixes or permutations others come up with.

I print this thing at 0.2mm layer in ABS, 50% infill.  No support, but a raft is recommended for ABS to avoid warpage.  
The SCAD code is annotated and pretty straightforward, but you do need to fill in a few variables.   Most of the logic complexity in the code is there to enable multi-color printing, which you don't have to use, but you can select various combinations of model components by commenting out variable defines (with two leading slashes: "//"), depending on how many models/colors you want to use.  You can of course modify the dimensions, layout, and content however you like, but that may require more code modifications to adjust the layout.

"my_name" of course  
"my_font" is used for all lettering.  There are a number of free license plate fonts available online.  I use one called "License Plate USA".  You can search for it.  See the OpenSCAD online reference for instructions on making a new font available to the rendering engine.  It is quite easy.  Note that font size and styles can be varied for individual text fields (see code for syntax).  You can also vary the base font if you wish.  
"background_model_path" is the full path/filename for your background model stl file -  for example, mount_rainier_4mm.stl, if you use the one I've provided.  You can also comment out the "background=true" definition to render a flat, plain background instead.   
I've used the OpenSCAD system variable $fn (fragment number) to set resolution of curved parts.  There are other ways to do this.  The default value of 100 looks great, but can take a long time to render (20+ minutes on slower computers).  Set it lower to get quick renders for dialing in your design, then turn it up for final stl rendering.

You can render individual components or combinations thereof by commenting out the boolean model variables (commenting out makes them implicitly false).  If you have variables commented out, OpenSCAD will generate warnings in the console, but you can ignore these.  They don't prevent model rendering.

• Part 1 - White (as described above; enable only parts 1,4,5)
  • Part 2 - Blue (relief mountain graphics, name, and year tab; enable only parts 2,4,5,6,7)
  • Part 3 - Red (base for incised lettering; enable part 3, disable all others)

I decided to do some spring-cleaning and it quickly became apparent that I would have to deal with my router. Normally it would simply stand on the edge of the desk, occasionally being tugged (mostly my cat) to the floor.   
So I set out to create the following mounting frame for the Technicolor TG589. It suspends the router about 60mm from the wall, allowing the ethernet cables to loop downwards. The mounting was broken up into 3 pieces simply to allow ease of construction.

The design was pretty straightforward. From the start I decided to use a three-part design which I would then glue together. I then designed a simple back plate which would correspond to a set of pre-existing screws used to mount my D-Link router. The retaining clips took a few test designs and prints (I had no information on the internal structure of the router casing) which was then incorporated into two mirrored support frames. I then measure the distance I would have to move the router away from the wall to accommodate the network cables. Assembly is simply:
Simply use the standard mix of Acetone and waste ABS. Find a nice flat surface to assemble the bits onto. A sheet of glass works pretty well.Start with one side, filling the pockets on the support frame with glue. Move over to the back plate apply glue to the nubs and the contact area of the support spine. Keeping the back plate flat on the work surface, move the side frame into position. For me, both pieces sat firmly on the surface and needed not further support. Repeat with the other side frame.
